docs\guides\ai-integration.md:233:## Session Recording for AI-Driven Debugging
docs\guides\ai-integration.md:235:Session recording is the foundational substrate for AI-driven debugging in 
civ-engine. It allows agents to:
docs\guides\ai-integration.md:243:import { SessionReplayer } from 'civ-engine';
docs\guides\ai-integration.md:245:const replayer = SessionReplayer.fromBundle(bundle, { worldFactory });
docs\guides\building-a-game.md:572:When players hit bugs in a built game, the most valuable artifact is a 
deterministic record of the session up to that moment. `SessionRecorder` captures everything needed to replay: initial 
state, every command submission, per-tick events and diffs, periodic snapshots. Players annotate "the bug happened 
here" via `recorder.addMarker({ kind: 'annotation', text: '...' })`, then the bundle is shared (file + JSON) for the 
team - or for an AI agent - to load and replay.
docs\guides\building-a-game.md:574:See [Session Recording](./session-recording.md) for the canonical reference.
docs\guides\concepts.md:224:- **`SessionRecorder` / `SessionReplayer` / `SessionBundle` / `SessionSink` / 
`SessionSource` / `MemorySink` / `FileSink` / `Marker` / `RecordedCommand`** - capture deterministic, replayable 
bundles of any World run; load + replay + selfCheck; companion adapter `scenarioResultToBundle()`. See 
`docs/guides/session-recording.md`.
docs\guides\debugging.md:439:## Replay-Based Debugging via Session Recording
docs\guides\debugging.md:441:For non-trivial issues - especially bugs that surface only after long playthroughs - 
`SessionRecorder` captures a deterministic record that can be replayed and inspected at any tick. Markers let players 
or developers annotate "this is when the bug happened" so the debug loop starts at the right moment instead of 
scrubbing linearly.
